HEADWORD: dybbuk
<hw>dyb"buk</hw> <pr>(d⟦icr⟧b"b⟦ucr⟧k; Hebrew d⟦emac⟧*b⟦oomac⟧k")</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>dybbuks</plw>; Hebr.
<plw>dybbukim</plw> <pr>(d⟦emac⟧`b⟦oomac⟧k*⟦emac⟧m")</pr>.</plu>
<fld>(Jewish folklore)</fld> <def>the wandering soul of a dead person,
or a demon, that enters the body of a living person and controls that
body's behavior. It may be exorcised by religious rites.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> dibbuk.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

